---

<DocsLayout title="Kraft Components" sidebar={kraftSidebar} description="Component model, props, lifecycle hooks, and composition in Kraft">

<h1>Components</h1>

<p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
  Everything in Kraft is a component. Here's how they work.
</p>

<h2>The component model</h2>

<p>Every Kraft component is a Kotlin class that extends <code>Component&lt;PROPS&gt;</code> and implements one method: <code>render()</code>.</p>

<Code code={`class Greeting(ctx: Ctx<Props>) : Component<Greeting.Props>(ctx) {
    data class Props(val name: String)

    override fun VDom.render() {
        h2 { +"Hello, ${'$'}{props.name}!" }
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<p>Alongside the class, you define a <strong>factory function</strong> so other components can use it in the HTML DSL:</p>

<Code code={`@Suppress("FunctionName")
fun Tag.Greeting(name: String) = comp(
    Greeting.Props(name = name)
) { Greeting(it) }`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<p>Now any parent component can write:</p>

<Code code={`override fun VDom.render() {
    Greeting(name = "World")
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h2>Component types</h2>

<h3>Component with props</h3>

<p>The most common type. Props are a <code>data class</code> — immutable, type-safe, and IDE-friendly.</p>

<Code code={`class UserCard(ctx: Ctx<Props>) : Component<UserCard.Props>(ctx) {
    data class Props(
        val name: String,
        val email: String,
        val role: String = "member",  // Default values work
    )

    override fun VDom.render() {
        ui.card {
            noui.content {
                ui.header { +props.name }
                noui.description { +props.email }
            }
            noui.extra.content {
                ui.label { +props.role }
            }
        }
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h3>PureComponent (no props)</h3>

<p>For components that don't need external data — pages, layouts, root components:</p>

<Code code={`class DashboardPage(ctx: NoProps) : PureComponent(ctx) {
    override fun VDom.render() {
        ui.container {
            ui.header H1 { +"Dashboard" }
            // ...
        }
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<p><code>PureComponent</code> is a convenience alias for <code>Component&lt;Any?&gt;</code> with <code>NoProps</code> context.</p>

<h3>Functional components</h3>

<p>For simple, stateless rendering — no class needed:</p>

<Code code={`val Badge = component { name: String, color: String ->
    ui.with(color).label { +name }
}

// Usage
override fun VDom.render() {
    Badge("Admin", "red")
    Badge("Active", "green")
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<p>Functional components support up to 10 parameters.</p>

<h2>Lifecycle hooks</h2>

<p>Components have four lifecycle hooks:</p>

<Code code={`class LiveSearch(ctx: Ctx<Props>) : Component<LiveSearch.Props>(ctx) {
    data class Props(val query: String)

    init {
        lifecycle {
            onMount {
                // Component is now in the DOM
                // ${'`'}dom${'`'} property gives you the HTMLElement
                console.log("Mounted at", dom?.tagName)
            }

            onUpdate {
                // Component re-rendered (props or state changed)
            }

            onUnmount {
                // Component removed from DOM
                // Streams auto-unsubscribe, but clean up other resources here
            }

            onNextProps { newProps, oldProps ->
                // Parent sent new props
                if (newProps.query != oldProps.query) {
                    reload()
                }
            }
        }
    }

    override fun VDom.render() {
        // ...
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<p><strong>Key point:</strong> Stream subscriptions (via <code>subscribingTo()</code>) auto-unsubscribe when the component unmounts. You don't need to clean them up manually.</p>

<h2>Component references</h2>

<p>Sometimes a parent needs to call methods on a child. Use <code>ComponentRef</code>:</p>

<Code code={`class DrawingApp(ctx: NoProps) : PureComponent(ctx) {

    // Create a ref tracker for the SignaturePad component
    private val padRef = ComponentRef.Tracker<SignaturePad>()

    override fun VDom.render() {
        // The SignaturePad component, tracked by our ref
        SignaturePad {
            // configuration...
        }.track(padRef)

        // Use the ref to access the child component
        padRef { pad ->
            ui.button {
                onClick { pad.clear() }
                +"Clear signature"
            }

            if (pad.isEmpty()) {
                ui.red.label { +"No signature yet" }
            }
        }
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<p>The <code>padRef &#123; ... &#125;</code> block only renders when the ref is attached — it's safe by design.</p>

<h2>Composing components</h2>

<p>Components compose naturally through the HTML DSL:</p>

<Code code={`class App(ctx: NoProps) : PureComponent(ctx) {
    override fun VDom.render() {
        div(classes = "app") {
            NavBar()
            ui.container {
                Sidebar()
                MainContent()
            }
            Footer()
        }
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h3>Passing callbacks</h3>

<p>Components communicate upward through callback props:</p>

<Code code={`class TodoItem(ctx: Ctx<Props>) : Component<TodoItem.Props>(ctx) {
    data class Props(
        val text: String,
        val done: Boolean,
        val onToggle: () -> Unit,
        val onDelete: () -> Unit,
    )

    override fun VDom.render() {
        ui.item {
            ui.checkbox {
                input(type = InputType.checkBox) {
                    checked = props.done
                    onChange { props.onToggle() }
                }
                label { +props.text }
            }
            ui.red.icon.button {
                onClick { props.onDelete() }
                icon.trash()
            }
        }
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h3>The <code>shouldRedraw</code> optimization</h3>

<p>By default, components redraw whenever props change. Override <code>shouldRedraw</code> to skip unnecessary renders:</p>

<Code code={`override fun shouldRedraw(nextProps: Props): Boolean {
    return nextProps != props  // Only redraw if props actually changed
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<p>Since <code>Props</code> is a data class, <code>!=</code> does a structural comparison — this is efficient and correct.</p>

<h2>Accessing app services</h2>

<p>Components can access app-level services through the attribute system:</p>

<Code code={`override fun VDom.render() {
    // These are available in any component
    val router = router                 // Navigation
    val modals = modals                 // Show modals
    val toasts = toasts                 // Show notifications
    val popups = popups                 // Show popups and context menus
    val responsive = responsiveCtrl()   // Screen size info
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

    <p>These are injected via Kraft's attribute system — no manual wiring needed. See <a href="/ultra/kraft/overlays">Overlays</a>
        for modals, toasts, and popups. See <a href="/ultra/kraft/utilities">Utilities</a> for responsive design.</p>

    <h2>Keys for list rendering</h2>

    <p>When rendering a list of items, set a <code>key</code> on each element so Preact can efficiently track which
        items changed, moved, or were removed:</p>

    <Code code={`ui.list {
    items.forEach { item ->
        noui.item {
            key = item.id  // stable, unique identifier
            +item.name
        }
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>Without keys, Preact re-creates every element on each render. With keys, it only updates what actually changed.
        Use a stable identifier (database ID, unique string) — not the list index.</p>

    <Code code={`// Also works on components
users.forEach { user ->
    UserCard(user) // implicit key from props

    // Or set explicitly on the wrapper
    div {
        key = user.id
        UserCard(user)
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Raw HTML with <code>unsafe</code></h2>

    <p>The <code>unsafe</code> block injects raw HTML strings directly into the DOM, bypassing the type-safe DSL:</p>

    <Code code={`div {
    unsafe {
        +"""<em>This is raw HTML</em>"""
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <Aside>The name is a hint. Raw HTML means raw risk. If the content comes from user input, an API, or a database, you
        are one unsanitized string away from an XSS attack. Always sanitize with a library like DOMPurify before
        injecting untrusted content.
    </Aside>

    <Code code={`// SAFE: sanitize untrusted content before injecting
import io.peekandpoke.kraft.addons.marked.markdown2html

div {
    unsafe {
        // markdown2html uses DOMPurify internally
        +markdown2html(untrustedMarkdown)
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h3>Key the parent of <code>unsafe</code></h3>

    <p>Preact cannot diff raw HTML — it treats the entire <code>unsafe</code> block as an opaque blob. On each
        re-render, the raw DOM is destroyed and recreated from scratch. To prevent this, set a <code>key</code> on the
        parent element. If the key doesn't change, Preact preserves the DOM subtree:</p>

    <Code code={`div {
    key = "article-${'$'}{article.id}"
    unsafe {
        +article.htmlContent
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>Without the key, every component re-render rebuilds the raw HTML DOM — which is wasteful for large content and
        causes visible flicker. With a stable key, the DOM is only rebuilt when the key changes.</p>

